"The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky," Sinclair writes, "here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," a choking, asphyxiating testament to their callous disregard for the world they despoil.

The workers, mere cogs in their relentless machine, are treated as expendable, their pains and plight as irrelevant as the soot that clings to their bodies. Sinclair reveals, "So from the top to the bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." The owners, unencumbered by law or regulation, force their employees to toil in squalor, their backs bent under the yoke of unending labor. "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers," Sinclair laments, his words cutting like a blade to the heart of the system that allows such misery to persist.

And so, the workers are left to rot, their lives snuffed out like candles in the darkness of Packingtown, with no recourse, no hope, no escape from the despair that is their lot. Their only solace is the cold embrace of the grave, and the memory of the cold, hard truth that they were once alive, breathing, and free.

In the grand tapestry of literature, each author weaves an intricate design to ensnare the reader's consciousness and tug at their heartstrings. Some, like F. Scott Fitzgerald, employ a linguistic alchemy, intermingling adjectives and nouns in unorthodox unions to cast a certain spell upon the reader. Fitzgerald's magnum opus, "The Great Gatsby," is a veritable smorgasbord of such techniques. He imbues symbols with meaning, then wields them like a blade, cleaving the very fabric of reality.

Fitzgerald's chromatic symphony is a masterclass in evocation. White and gray, gold and green, red and pink, each hue is a note in his sonata of symbolism. The color white, for instance, is his scepter of uniformity, his banner of high station. In the novel's beginning, this color is ubiquitous. Daisy and Jordan are ever cloaked in white, a chaste shroud that belies their true nature. Nick, at Gatsby's resplendent parties, is a ghostly figure in white flannels. Even the mundane becomes resplendent in this color—Nick's journey to work is a descent into the "white chasms of lower New York," and the names on his timetable are as gray as the land of ashes.

But Fitzgerald does not merely paint with his colors; he uses them to signify, to underscore meaning. Daisy, after a prolonged absence from the white world, reemerges, "dressed in white," a specter of her former self, a mere appendage to Gatsby's dream. The white roadster she drives is a ghostly apparition, a reminder of her past. Gray, too, is his tool, a veil of indifference. The "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" is a shroud, a barrier between her and the world. Even the dreary "gray cars" and "gray land" are tainted with this pallid hue.

Fitzgerald's use of color is not merely decorative; it is a language, a cipher that whispers secrets to the astute reader. It is a dance of light and shadow, a symphony of hue and tone. And in this dance, Fitzgerald leads us through the labyrinth of his novel, painting a portrait of a society where uniformity is a disease, and the color of one's skin is a badge of one's station.

In the sun-baked heart of San Diego County, where the land yields abundantly to the kind touch of the sun and the gentle caress of the sea, the soil is not merely tilled but kissed into life. Here, the fields are a tapestry of green, woven with the threads of tomatoes, citrus, and leaves that whisper in the breeze. Squash and broccoli, herbs and berries, the sweet kiss of peaches and lemons, and the fiery dance of peppers - all grow here, nurtured by the mild, sun-kissed climate and the patient hands of farmers who tend to the earth like it were their own flesh.

A market for such organic bounty stirs, a hunger that has birthed a community of growers who offer not just sustenance, but experience. Tours of their earthly sanctuaries, where the air is alive with the song of birds and the hum of bees, where the soil is rich with life and the spirit of the land. Here, the farmer finds not just a way to fill their pockets, but to fill their soul.

Yet, the path is not without its trials. The organic way, it seems, is a dance with hardship. The absence of chemicals is a burden, a calloused hand that needs constant care. Pests and weeds, they grow in the absence of poisons, and the soil, it demands a more intimate touch, a constant tending. The scale may be small, but the heart is wide, and the land, it gives back - in biodiversity, in joy, in spirit.

The parcel chosen, a testament to nature's resilience, is a patchwork of chaparral, exotic grasslands, and oak woodlands, nestled against the ancient heart of the Cleveland National Forest. It is a land that breathes, that lives, that is home to more than a hundred souls - some endangered, some declining, all precious. Here, the ghosts of the past whisper in the wind, the echoes of Native American feet and cattle hooves, the ghosts of cordwood sellers who once called this land theirs.

The land, it speaks of a heritage, a responsibility. It calls for more than just tending, more than just tilling. It calls for a partnership, a dance with nature, a symphony of life. And so, the farmer seeks not just the help of government, but the wisdom of the land, the spirit of the earth. For this is not just a farm, but a sanctuary, a testament to the power of the organic way, a call to arms for the future of the land.

Culture, it is said, doth play a significant role in the dance of negotiation. One might define it as much by what it doth not encompass as by what it doth. It is not a homogenous beast, nor a singular thing, nor uniform in its form. Assertions such as "all Russians are stubborn," or "all Japanese are accommodating," are broad and simplistic, mere generalizations that serve to obscure rather than illuminate. A negotiator would be well-served to understand the import of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture's attitude may impact the table talks. When one approaches a foreign shore, one experiences it through the lens of their own culture, and comparisons, like the ghosts of old battles, are inevitable.

To understand a foreign culture or mindset, one must delve deep, like a miner seeking gold. It may involve poring over history, grappling with prejudices, or simply observing the patterns that unfold before one's eyes. Rather than judge or attempt to reshape, one must simply accept a culture for what it is, and work within its bounds, especially so when one finds oneself at the table with a weaker hand. And when on 'away' soil, respect for traditions and beliefs can be the key that unlocks the door to progress.

Culture, it should be noted, is not confined to national or international borders. Within a given nation, companies forge their own cultures, each unique as a snowflake. Some may demand long hours, others a relaxed pace. Signs of corporate culture are visible in dress codes, communication styles, and hiring practices. Some encourage philanthropy from any quarter, while others steer it to "company-approved" causes. The diversity of thought within American corporations, from coast to coast, is a testament to this. Some cultures may appear uniform to the outsider, but beneath the surface lies a world as complex and varied as the human heart.

Values, too, are paramount. If a culture values saving face or communal harmony, a negotiator will not shame his company or superior to gain the upper hand. Conversely, a negotiator who hails from a culture that prizes a hard bargain will not settle for the first offer. A negotiator should be well-versed in these generalities before stepping into the arena. Yet, to truly make the negotiation effective, one must learn something of their opponent on a personal level. For it is not just the culture that shapes us, but the individuals who embody it.

"The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God.'" The words of Psalm 14 and the opening of St. Anselm's argument are but the first gust in the wind of theological inquiry. The same storm, one might say, bears Thomas Aquinas' words, who, like his predecessor, seeks to prove the existence of God. However, to compare their arguments, we must first accept that they both believe in the God of the Bible, for any other deity would muddy the waters of our discussion.

St. Anselm, in his Proslogion, suggests a path of self-discovery, a journey inward to find the divine. He argues that God's existence is inherent in our understanding, and thus, we cannot conceive of His non-existence. This is a faith-based logic, one that requires no empirical evidence, but rather, trusts in the truth that we already know within our souls. This is a common theme in Christianity, a belief that faith, not facts, is the key to unlocking the mysteries of the universe.

Thomas Aquinas, however, treads a different path. He believes that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence alone. This approach, he argues, is beneficial for evangelism, as it allows one to persuade others through logic, rather than relying on their willingness to accept the unknown. His Five Ways are a demonstration of this logic: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument suggests that God's existence is a logical necessity, like knowing the piece of a puzzle that's missing, but its shape and existence can be known through the rest.

In both cases, we see a belief in God's existence, though the path to that belief is different, and neither provides a holistic basis for belief. For while faith and reason may lead us to God, they do not necessarily bring us to the same place, and perhaps, that's where the truth lies, in the journey, not just the destination.

In the waning days of the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born, latter to be known as Buddha. Over the span of his mortal existence, he left behind the trappings of the world and attained enlightenment, setting forth a path that would foster the birth of Buddhism - the most orthodox of which is Theravada. This faith, now some twenty-five hundred years old, bears little resemblance to its original form. Take, for instance, the island of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike partake in this ritual, a practice that Buddha himself never taught. Such variances extend from surface customs to the very essence of the religion. The Theravada community, both monastic and lay, has had to modify its doctrinal principles over time, a process shaped by forces both within and without, both friendly and malicious.

I shall employ a few terms throughout this discourse. Internal forces are those born of the adherents of Buddhism, regardless of their monastic status. External forces are those from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or seek to harm the Buddhist community, born of a negative perception of the faith. Benign forces are those that neither wish to harm nor aid the community, though their actions may have unintended consequences.

First, let us explore the fundamental tenets of this religion - the doctrines that lie at the heart of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the Three Jewels of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma, the essence of the Buddha's teachings, is comprised of the Tripitaka - the Three Baskets. The Sutta Pitaka contains the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka the metaphysical components. The notion of Anatta - no self, Dukkha - inherent suffering, and Anicca - impermanence of all things - are central to this metaphysics. Only by acknowledging these truths can one escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. Along with this, lobha - desire, dosa - hatred, and moha - delusion - will cease, and one shall become enlightened. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for life, for laymen and monks alike. Laymen adhere to five precepts: I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not partake in intoxicants. Monks are bound by many more disciplinary rules. The most fundamental teaching is the Four Noble Truths. First, Dukkha - life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

In the annals of world history, few rivalries burn with such fervency as the one that once engulfed the United States and Mexico, a feud that raged for fifty-seven long years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The apex of this enmity was reached during the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, when the United States, like a hungry wolf, devoured the territories of Texas and the American Southwest, leaving Mexico bereft and humbled. In the interim, numerous skirmishes erupted between the two nations, not unlike the sparks that ignite a prairie fire, until the First World War finally extinguished the flames. (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

The seeds of this enmity were sown in the early days, when Americans and Mexicans clashed over matters of religion, culture, and tradition, as well as in the realm of material interests. It was a clash of ideals, a struggle for dominance, much like the ideological wars that have divided nations throughout history. The Americans, inheritors of the English way, and the Mexicans, heirs to the Spanish, were locked in a dance of distrust, a pas de deux of suspicion. (Frahm 2001 p. 86).

The list of disputes between Mexico and the United States, as chronicled by Diehl and Goerts (2000), is a testament to this enduring enmity. Seventeen grievances, each a chip in the armor of their shared border, each a testament to the constant skirmishes waged over territory. Bandits and outlaws, like ghostly specters, haunted the borders, their raids a constant reminder of the simmering conflict. (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).

As the years wore on, the tide of the rivalry turned. Mexico, once a proud, independent nation, became increasingly dependent on the United States, a new, more insidious form of occupation. And as American ambitions shifted, from territorial expansion to economic intervention, the rivalry began to wane, like a dying ember. (Schmitt 1974 p. 109-110).

Fifteen years ago, I found myself felled by a malady I had never known, a shadow that descended upon me in the prime of my life. I had been a nurse, a profession chosen out of a desperation for the safety and certainty that had eluded me in my youth. "Always work, always sickness," the words echoed through my adolescence and beyond, and so I forged ahead, even as my heart yearned for the realms of science and journalism. But fate had other plans, and at forty-six, I found myself crippled, alone, and penniless.

The world shifted beneath me, a storm that has raged for fifteen long years. I am a man adrift, clinging to Social Security Disability, a lifeline that has seen me through, yet left me bereft of anything truly my own. Each day is a battle, a test of my resolve, my security, my very self. Yet, there is one truth etched in these harsh years: I would not have endured were it not for the kindness of my family and a few steadfast friends. When calamity strikes, one cannot stand alone.

Emergencies, they come in all shapes and sizes, and no preparations can guard against them all. We must learn to trust each other again, to lend a hand, to seek help when we need it. We cannot rely on a crumbling government to catch us when we fall. Our forefathers did not conquer the Rockies alone; they rode in wagon trains, united in their quest. And so, I say, be ready. But do not forget, as you gather your supplies and prepare your defenses, to open your heart to your neighbors.

I have my disaster kit, my first aid, my water purifying tablets, and my plastic sheeting. I have flashlights and batteries, candles and matches, cans of food. I have a small farm and a wood stove, if the land and resources allow. But I also have a community, and I will not let it be forgotten.

Why do creatures unfurl in this peculiar manner, as if governed by some unseen hand? Are there limitations or boundaries that dictate the course of their evolution? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson mused, "Even now, the zoologist has barely begun to whisper in the language of mathematics the simplest organic shapes." Yet, here we stand, delving into the unknown, seeking to unravel the mechanisms that guide the transformation and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change in Prunum. Our investigation encompasses a fusion of mathematical modeling and experimental inquiry, a symphony of the theoretical and the tangible.

We employ X-radiographic images of Prunum species to pinpoint quantitative parameters, which are then fed into the software program CerioShell. Our models, like the shell itself, are a journey through 360 degrees of space, a spiral dance around the central axis known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls expand, the continuous line dividing each, the suture—these are the notes in our symphony, each one a whisper of the shell's story.

The shell, a testament to time and space, can be observed from various perspectives: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. In the usual orientation, the aperture points towards the viewer, and the apex, like a lighthouse, points skyward. The animal, a sailor in its shell, extends through an aperture, a window to the world outside.

To chart the course of the aperture, one must trace its path through time and space as the mollusk builds its shell. This trajectory, a graph of coordinates, can be mathematically represented, allowing us to vary parameters and modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The toll of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained stubbornly unchanged for a decade. As it approaches the end of the Millennium Development Goals, the nation's progress in water and sanitation far outpaces its advances in child and maternal health. The causes of this disparity are manifold, pointing to a need not for isolated interventions but for a fortification of the health system as a whole.

Indonesia has seen an increase in births attended by skilled workers, with 72% now meeting the target. Yet, this figure includes traditional midwives who lack the medical prowess to intervene in complicated pregnancies. Their inclusion skews the numbers, a stark reminder of the work yet to be done. Moreover, the rate of diarrheal cases treated by health professionals in children under five has dropped, and postnatal care remains a concern, with low rates nationwide.

Caesarean section rates remain low, hovering around 4%, with urban areas performing significantly better than rural ones. This disparity underscores the inequitable distribution of healthcare services, heavily favoring urban areas. Additionally, the gap between the poorest and richest quintiles in service utilization is a staggering 27%, highlighting the financial barriers to healthcare for the impoverished.

With these issues in mind, the question arises: should Indonesia focus on targeted programmatic approaches or bolster the overall healthcare system? Programmatic interventions offer clear, manageable objectives and faster results. However, they have their drawbacks. Heavy investment in one area often starves others of funding and resources. Furthermore, the proliferation of uncoordinated, duplicative programs leads to an increase in administrative burdens.

Victorian literature, with its meticulous attention to detail and abiding by the aristocratic norms of the era, is often constrained by a rigid adherence to tradition. Yet, amidst this rigid structure, two novels stand out: Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These works, like a lone wolf among the flock, embrace the strange and the untoward, employing a tincture of mystery and the bizarre that lends depth to their characters and insights into their motivations and emotions. Dickens, in Oliver Twist, captures this essence as he writes:

“And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” (Dickens, 220)

The two novels employ this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, though their function varies. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences often unveil Oliver’s inner turmoil, his fears, and his awareness of the true nature of the events around him. When the shooting of Oliver is finally revisited in chapter 28, he relives the experience as if in a dream, grappling for help. The passage underscores his lack of control over the events that transpired, as well as his dire physical state, reflected in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself numbs all his senses, leaving him to experience his despair anew, unshocked by the pain, which now flows as constant and is linked with fear rather than surprise. This lack of control over his fate forces the question: Whose will brought about his misfortune? For it was certainly not his own. The growing sense of defeat in Oliver is palpable, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him into accepting this despair, so that he can no longer react, even in the face of his own life.

“And the day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting ours.” (Dickens)

A couple of years back, I found myself toiling as a tutor in an after-school program, helping young ones with their studies. My talents lay in the English and reading realms, yet I was roped into assisting a lad named Adrian, who was struggling mightily with his letters. The boy's predicament was peculiar. Some letters he'd pronounce as if he'd been born to the tongue, others he'd mangle like a drunken man. He hailed from a Latin household, but his English was as smooth as a river's flow. We wrestled with his struggles until fate intervened in the form of his mother, who swept into the room like a storm at sea. She spoke no English, only Spanish, and my grasp of the tongue was tenuous at best. We managed to communicate, though it was clumsy and stilted. And then it struck me like a thunderclap: the boy could read, but he was lost in the alphabet's maze.

This tale serves to illuminate the shadow cast by language barriers in our schools, particularly here in California. It's not always as clear as it seems. Even a child who speaks English like a native can be lost in the labyrinth of letters. We agree that this problem festers, so what's the remedy? In Adrian's case, tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciation, sufficed. Yet for those who barely speak the tongue, the solution is a tangled web.

The dual language system, a notion that's been given short shrift, could be a boon. It's not just for Spanish-speaking children, but for all. Research shows that those in such programs outperform their peers. Yet there's a fear that it's a waste of resources, that the majority will derive no benefit. This is a fallacy. If we integrated these programs into our classrooms, all children would reap the rewards. But how best to implement this? Should we insist on bilingual teachers? No, that's unrealistic. But having bilingual aides or tutors, that's something we could manage.

From the moment we first draw breath, we are told there exists a force greater than ourselves, a void we cannot fathom. Some of us are instructed in its ways, while others turn to the temple or delve into the depths of their souls for answers. Many embrace the creeds passed down by those who came before, but some scoff at the notion, rejecting any notion of a world beyond our own egos. We traverse different paths, each seeking to define ourselves through our unique perceptions of the divine. We search for a guiding light to break the shadows that surround us.

"Cardinal," my father replied when I inquired about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, the rain's relentless drumming on the tin roof accompanied by the steady rhythm of our cigarettes. The gutters gushed, extinguishing the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain, his eyes reflecting an eternal search and a lingering memory. His once ample frame now hung loosely on him, his hair thinned and sparse. His gaze lingered on the rain, avoiding mine. I felt isolated, frightened, and unable to express the pain I would feel when he was gone, lest it become a reality for both of us. I embraced him tightly, moved my chair closer, and stared out into the June twilight's falling rain with him.

In December, five days after I reached the age of twenty-two, my father passed. The doctors' projections were bested only by the chemotherapy and radiation, which prolonged his suffering. What purpose it served, I could not comprehend. I lay in bed for three nights, curled into a ball and awaiting the news. No one telephoned.

The so-called "Gothic Novel," in essence a strange marriage of "Old" and "New," as Ian Watt posits in his study, has been both reviled and revered, deemed shallow or profound, and celebrated for its capacity to evoke the "terrible sublime" (Burke). The first of such tales, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, fused the ancient and modern to birth the nascent Gothic mode, introducing a novel method of literary expression. Walpole, in his crafting of "A Gothic Story," wove together old theatrical elements and new mimicry of nature, as seen in modern novels, to create a unique blend that would resonate through time. The Gothic genre, with its throwbacks to medieval theater, architecture, and tradition, baffled contemporaries, appearing archaic and unsophisticated in the face of modern societal and literary progress. Yet, it is this very fusion that allows Gothic to endure, forever new and obsolete to the displaced reader.

Chivalry, a cornerstone of Gothic fiction, is a prominent theme in the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Walpole's work preserves and transforms the medieval ideal of chivalry, the training of a proper knight, reflecting his disillusionment with contemporary society. Through chivalric concepts and manners, Walpole romanticizes the past, hinting at the future evolution of Gothic to Romanticism, as a means to aspire to a better present. Walpole, a man entangled in political turmoil and unfair accusations, may have felt the morality and inherent goodness of the Gothic era had vanished in his contemporaries. This is evident in characters like Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits before our eyes ever meet him. His description includes phrases of a "gallant and courteous Knight," a figure exaggerated, as is the Gothic tendency towards excess (66).

The ceaseless dance of goods through the vast expanse of commerce, from the first whisper of a customer's desire to the final denouement of satisfaction, is what we know as supply chain management. Conceived in the crucible of 1982 by one Keith Oliver, a man of enterprise, it is the art of planning, executing, and guiding the ebb and flow of the supply chain to satisfy the customer's need with swift, efficient grace.

Six are the cornerstones upon which this edifice is built: production, supply, inventory, location, conveyance, and knowledge. The manager, like the conductor of an orchestra, employs these elements to ensure the symphony of commerce plays to the customer's delight.

**Production**, the first and foundational step, is the birthplace of the supply chain's essence. Here, the managers, as the midwives of industry, must discern the will of the market, the mother from whom all demands are born. The market, a vast, impersonal entity, tells us what the customer wants, and the manager, like a seer, deciphers its omens. Once the market's secrets are revealed, the manager decides what products shall be born and how many of them shall see the light of day. The where and how follow, with the manager choosing the plant that best serves the customer's needs, balancing volume and quality in the delicate dance of production.

The next key element, **supply**, is the strategic heart of the supply chain. Here, the manager decides the core capabilities of the facility and the paths of partnerships with others. For a single product, a company may have many divisions, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must choose the best division for each process, like a master selecting the most skilled artisans for a task. Outsourcing may be the manager's choice, to quicken the pace, to inject flexibility and reduce costs, or to maintain the low, steady hum of efficiency.

In the grimy heart of Burma, a land where the junta's iron grip stifles the voice of the people, a lone figure stands, cardboard sign held aloft like a flag of defiance. The words scrawled in Sharpie are a stark reminder: "Hitler lives." Burma, or Myanmar, a nation where the scent of violence and oppression hang heavy in the air, has a history of subjugation that echoes through the generations. The monks, their saffron robes a beacon of hope, took to the streets in 2007, their chants echoing through the empty halls of power. But the junta's response was swift and brutal, monasteries laid waste, journalists imprisoned, and a photojournalist named Kenji Nagai gunned down for the crime of bearing witness.

The world is not new to such atrocities. The Roman emperors, with their god-king pretenses, the Japanese emperors and their divine right to rule, even the current president, Bush, with his weekly communions with Ted Haggard, all share a common thread of absolute power and the suppression of dissent. The Tiananmen Square massacre, where the cries of freedom were silenced by tanks, the Rwandan genocide, where the river ran red with innocent blood, and Hitler's Third Reich, where the Holocaust's shadow still looms over Europe - these are but a few instances of humanity's darkest hour.

The sign, Ellen Page's sign, is a testament to the human spirit's refusal to be broken. It is a beacon of defiance in the face of tyranny, a spark that can ignite a flame. For the world is not new to darkness, but perhaps, through such acts of bravery, it can be made anew.

In this brutal, unforgiving world of jazz, Duke Ellington carved out a legacy that endured like a ancient stone beneath the earth. He was a master of his craft, a damn near sage in the realm of sound. His fingers danced upon the keys of his piano, subtle as the whisper of wind through leaves, yet his compositions were as vast and intricate as the darkest nights under the New Orleans moon.

Ellington's genius lay in his ability to shape his orchestra much like a god shapes a world. The piano, his instrument, was a voice in this symphony of souls he conducted. He composed pieces that were rich and complex, each note a pebble in a river that flowed with the individual talents of his band members. He crafted a stage where soloists could improvise like the wild, untamed spirits of the South, yet he also wrote phrases and melodies that called for each player's unique voice. In doing so, he created a tone so distinct, so original, that it echoed across the decades.

The Grove Music dictionary, a tome of sacred knowledge, speaks of Ellington's sound and innovation. It mentions Creole Love Call, a piece wherein he used the human voice as a jazz instrument, adding texture and color without the burden of lyrics. This early experiment was but one of many examples of Ellington's ear for tone and his ability to complement the voices of his soloists. Creole Love Call, a slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues, is a tapestry of call and response between voice and reeds, each chorus a dance of the soul. Chorus by chorus, Ellington weaves a spellbinding narrative, from the smooth, melodic opening to the rough, growling finish. The final chorus, a return to the first, sees the voice take on the sound of the "growl" technique, soloing like an instrument of the gods. It is a masterclass in tone, a symphony of sound.

Hot and Bothered, recorded the year following, finds Ellington combining his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. Bubber Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing engage in a call and response, the vocal elements of Miley's playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox's voice creating a sound that is rich and complementary. It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) extends these ideas, with Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton introducing the melody on muted trombone, his sound as unique and haunting as a ghost in the night.

Ellington's use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to his pieces is but one of the many stylistic traits that permeated his work. He was a composer of the highest order, a pioneer in the art of jazz. His legacy lives on, as eternal as the stars above the Mississippi delta.

She'd always felt that something was missing, a void that gnawed at her, a yearning that refused to be sated. It began when she was barely fourteen, as she stumbled into the labyrinth of adolescence. Three years hence, at seventeen, she still sought, though her hunger had shifted from thing to person. Yet, no youth appealed to her, not even those who made their clumsy advances. She puzzled over this, her mind a whirlwind of theories and conjectures, each as fleeting as the morning dew. So she lived, and questioned, and waited.

Quiet days at home, under the roof of her placid parents, were rare though she loved them well. Her father's calm demeanor, her mother's quiet fortitude, they never argued, not with each other, nor with their daughter. Except, perhaps, when she asserted her independence, her spirit wild as a stallion. Yet, she was their daughter, their beloved, her personality a beacon of light in their serene home.

But today was not one of those days. As she wandered the rooms, seeking some spark of inspiration for herself, she heard a cry, a wail that echoed through the house. It was her mother's voice, and it was filled with pain. She rushed to the kitchen, her heart pounding in her chest, her breath coming in short gasps. "Mother? Mother, what is wrong?" she cried out, her voice shaking.

She found her mother on the floor, writhing in agony, her breaths coming in short, sharp clips. "Ow," she gasped, her voice barely audible. "Sweet, take me to the hospital." Her daughter did not hesitate. She gathered her mother in her arms, her muscles straining under the weight, and carried her to the car. The drive was a blur, her mind filled with fear and worry, her heart pounding in her chest.

The hospital was a place of antiseptic and suffering, a place of fear and pain. But she did not sense it, for her mind was occupied with her mother. She rushed her inside, her voice echoing through the halls as she called for help. Doctors and nurses swarmed around them, their faces etched with worry, and one of them gently guided her to a chair, leaving her to sit in anxious anticipation.

It turned out, her mother had fallen from a stool, trying to reach a vase in the highest cabinet. The vase was untouched, but her mother's body had taken the brunt of the fall.

This study sought to illuminate the relationship between adherence to the "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as gauged by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", and the mitigation of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet, a variant of the Med diet, emphasizes the consumption of plant-based foods such as fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, while deeming animal products and saturated fats as less desirable. Moderate alcohol intake is permitted within this regimen.

Previous prospective studies have established an inverse correlation between compliance with the Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. In an intervention trial, the Med diet proved more effective than a low-fat diet in facilitating weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. However, these studies did not focus specifically on stroke or stroke-related mortality.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women, between the ages of 38 and 63, who were free from cardiovascular disease (CVD) or diabetes. Participants were drawn from the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort of 121,700 female nurses residing in 11 US states. Over the course of six assessments, from 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to evaluate nutrient intake over the preceding year. The FFQs underwent validation studies, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Cases without available records were deemed "probable" and included in the analysis, representing approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts.

To account for random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were computed (averaging scores from the two prior years). Adjustments were made for confounders, including age, smoking, body mass index (BMI), menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was employed to assess the relationship between the aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, with separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a reduced risk of both incident CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up period, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (both fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the highest aMed quintile exhibited a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In the year of Our Lord, two thousand and seven, the United States of America was beset by a calamitous financial crisis. Unemployment rose like a spectral tide, the housing market crumbled as if struck by a divine wrath, and many of her most vaunted corporations lay in ruin, their towers reduced to empty shells. This recession, a scourge upon the land, continues to this day, and we are compelled to inquire: how did this catastrophe come to pass, and how may we forestall its recurrence?

The roots of this calamity can be traced back to the Clinton administration, in the year of Our Lord nineteen hundred and ninety-nine, as the President sought to secure his reelection by pandering to the whims of the people. To this end, he relaxed lending restrictions, thus setting the stage for the sub-prime debacle that would unfold seven years hence. Steven Holmes, a journalist of the New York Times, warned of the perils that lay ahead: "Fannie Mae, the nation's largest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate-income people and felt pressure from stockholders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits." Holmes, in his prescient wisdom, foresaw the consequences of their folly: "But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." Thus, the seeds of our doom were sown.

The crisis was not a singular event, but a confluence of many factors. Among them was the emergence of a new and labyrinthine mortgage structure. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) became the order of the day, ensnaring more and more sectors of the economy in the housing market's grasp. This led to a state of overextension, a kind of mania that left households and financial markets alike vulnerable to even the slightest fluctuations in price.

The housing bubble, like some monstrous beast, burst forth with devastating force. The investment banks that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were left with a bitter taste in their mouths, for they were now confronted with debts in excess of four trillion dollars, accounting for nearly a third of our GDP. Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold for a pittance, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercially regulated entities. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, with their five trillion dollars in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September of two thousand and eight.

Ah, the realm of exposition.  A place where some authors take flight with their quill, their words painting vivid images that captivate, or a place where readers' eyes glaze over and their fingers fleetingly hover over the "Back" button, cursing the author's name.  Dr. Merlin, she has known such a fate, standing before her monitor, her brow furrowed, her voice raised in exasperation at the excess of words, the overwhelming tide of information.

Exposition, it is not your friend.

The lesson, "Show, don't tell," is well-known, yet it is a lesson that Dr. Merlin, she still struggles with.  Like a wayward horse, she finds herself atop a mountain of words, with naught but the silence of the desert and the echo of her own thoughts to meet her halfway.  The devil on her shoulder, it whispers, "Get the story on its way, get to the meat of it."  But the devil on the other shoulder, it urges, "Tell them every detail, every twist, every tear that makes up your characters."

Exposition, it is the simple telling of what has been, what is, what will be.  In the theater of words, it is the actor who takes the stage and spouts lines, the audience's eyes wide and ears alert, yet somehow, not fully engaged.  In the realm of fiction, it is the author who takes the pen and paints the picture, the canvas filled with details, yet the colors muted, the image blurry.

Consider the tale of the heroine and her love.  You would not expect, in the telling of their story, that the author would spend two pages, their words flowing like a river, the lovers only getting two lines of speech.  You would expect, you would crave, the author to flesh out the man, to show him through his words, his actions, his very being, how he loved his wife.  And you would expect the same from the woman, to see her through his eyes, to understand the depth of their bond, the richness of their love.  You would mourn his death with her, and in doing so, you would grow closer to her, to her heart, her dreams, her very essence.

In short, you would expect more than just the simple tale.  "They met, they married, he died."  A tale told too briefly, too plainly.  As a writer, you must provide more.  The bread, you must wrap it in meat, you must season it, you must let it rest.  You must let it become a feast, a symphony of words that captivates, that leaves the reader's heart aching, their soul yearning for more.  For that is the power of exposition, not to merely tell, but to weave a tapestry of words, a story that lives, that breathes, that is more than just words on a page.

In the chill of a Columbus dawn, I bore witness to two broadcasts from the belly of the beast, the city's appetite for the grim spectacle of its own making. The first, an NBC forum, spewed forth its tidings with a certain lethargic urgency. A man named Shad Hostettler, his features etched with the malevolence of a thousand lost souls, had been taken for the murder of his wife, her name a whisper on the wind. Her blood, spilled in the quiet of Ashley, Ohio, was but a fleeting tale, a mere two minutes' respite from the day's unsavory offerings. The second, a tale of a youth named Travis Buyers, shot down in the cold embrace of Sharon Woods, was told with a certain reserve, the color of his skin a shadow over the truth.

The third tale, a bullet's footprint upon a Med-Flight's metal skin, spoke of a .22 caliber's song, a dance with death. Crime-Stoppers, with their five-thousand dollar reward, were the symphony's conductors, the dance's choreographers. The fourth, a teaser for the weekend's storm, was but a fleeting thought, a whisper of the weather's wrath. The fifth, a robbery on Clime Road, was a report of a dark-skinned man, a Hoodie's specter, a vulture's cry. His features were described with a certain relish, the color of his skin a stark detail, a curiosity.

The final tale was of a man named Rene Rodriguez, a Hispanic drug kingpin, his sentence a curious thing, not twenty-five years, but three hundred months, a march of time. His hue, it seemed, was a detail to be noted, a curiosity, a whisper in the wind.

A bond between brothers, a tether that cannot be sundered, a bond as immutable as the wilds of the world, unyielding in its grip. Within it, emotions swirl like a storm, a tempestuous dance of love and loathing, of pride and jealousy, of cruelty and compassion. Brothers, they see themselves in each other, a mirror reflection in the eyes of their kin. It is in the direst of times that this bond reveals its true face, both in its grace and its malevolence. The cost is high, the price exacted in actions and their aftermath. To see oneself in a brother is to see not as others see, but as one truly is. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers wade through a verdant, vivid landscape, a stage for their futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with fierce pride in their climactic encounter, and only one emerges alive. This theme unfurls through the protagonist, Doodle, and his interactions with his brother, as well as through the narrator's eyes, which convey the protagonist's complex feelings and their impact on his actions.

The protagonist's heart is a battleground, a landscape sculpted by a single emotion: pride. From their first outing together to their final, fatal expedition, he feels a gnawing resentment towards Doodle. He sought a brother who could be his equal, one to share his world with, to race to Horsehead Landing and perch with in the great pine's top fork. But Doodle's frail heart, a fragile thing, made such dreams impossible. The young boy's head filled with wild fantasies, crushed in an instant. He, even, contemplated death's cold embrace for his brother, a thought born of bitter frustration. Yet, a simple smile from the child could melt his heart, a hope that gave his conviction a moment's pause. Deep within, a love for his brother burned, a love that could not be extinguished.

The human brain, a labyrinthine tapestry of thought and perception, has long been the subject of metaphor and inquiry, much like the ancient maps that once doubled for the unkown. Initially, it was likened to a simple wax tablet, plain and unchanging, yet it quickly evolved into the sprawling expanse of a parchment scroll, then the bound tomes of libraries, and now, the cold, unyielding circuit board of a machine.

To grasp the brain's enigma, consider the humble inputs of the senses, the eyes, ears, and fingertips that translate the world into electrochemical signals - a strange alchemy of flesh and fire. These signals are then woven through the brain's algorithms, a dance of bottom-up and top-down, where each step builds upon the last, like the scaffolding of a grand cathedral. The world is perceived, recognized, and understood, with the aid of the brain's attention, a fickle sentinel that guides our awareness through the tide of sensation.

Memory, too, is a vast and mysterious landscape, where information is encoded, stored, and maintained in the brain's strange architecture. The types of memory are as varied as the grains of sand on a desert shore, from the fleeting moments of sensory memory, to the vast expanse of long-term memory, where information is held in the very structure of proteins, as if carved into the stone of the mind.

Many are the models that seek to explain the brain's organization, from the human experience of memory retrieval, to the cold logic of computer science, and the dance of neurons. One such model, the semantic network, posits a web of nodes and links, where concepts are like stars in a constellated sky, connected by their relatedness, a web of meaning spun from the threads of thought.

In the realm of Aldous Huxley's Brave New World, a dystopian landscape looms large, where the specter of technology and capitalistic structures intertwine to create a chilling tableau. The citizens of this world, born into a system that prioritizes community over the individual, are conditioned from the cradle to pursue immediate gratification. They are, in truth, mere pawns in a grand design orchestrated by the World Controller, a puppet master who tugs at the strings of their existence. Through the lens of Marxist critique, the author's suspicions are laid bare, as the story unfolds like a cautionary tale against the excesses of economic systems.

Capitalism is laid bare in the novel's stark portrayal, where the Marxist concept of false consciousness prevails. The common folk, blinded by their own desires, are kept from understanding the true dynamics of their economic plight. Ideological control has rendered them slaves to their consumerist impulses, their wills subsumed into the machinery of capitalism. The conditioning they undergo, through hypnopædia, stokes the fires of consumption and indulgence, manipulated by the World Controller to maintain the status quo.

The notion of hegemony is evident in Huxley's vision, as the lower classes are kept in the dark about their own oppression. The Delta, Gamma, and Gamma classes, content in their stations, are merely cogs in a wheel, unaware of the manipulation that keeps them in their place. The upper classes, born with the ability to see beyond their stations, choose to remain silent, few exceptions like Bernard or other characters only serving to highlight the prevailing komplizen passive acceptance.

Human connections are as shallow as the novel's characters, each a carbon copy of the last. The lack of depth and complexity in their interactions mirrors the dehumanizing effects of technology and capitalism, robbing individuals of their free will and expression. Love, and the extremes of emotion, are absent, replaced by superficial interactions that reduce individuals to their physical attributes or fleeting encounters. This societal structure, a mirror of Marxist thought, reflects the proletariat's false sense of superiority, so long as they continue to consume, obey, and remain in the fold.

I've been abiding amongst these hallowed halls for near on two and a half years now, a span of four and a half learning seasons. The sprawl of this campus, once a vast and uncharted territory, now feels as crowded as a cathedral during mass. The East Halls, where I was once sequestered, stand as a testament to the campus's relentless expansion, a relic of times when vast stretches of untamed land lay between the student and the heart of knowledge. Now, those same fields are filled with sports arenas, or the new Creamery and health services building, and the encroachment of apartments, all bearing down on the dwindling sanctuaries of quiet contemplation.

In times past, these expanses were traversed by the sure-footed and the intrepid, but as the campus grew, so too did the distance between the student and the classroom. The bicycle, once a symbol of freedom and simplicity, now appears a necessity, a means to navigate this ever-expanding labyrinth.

I spoke to a fellow traveler, a comrade in this journey of academia, who had recently rediscovered the pleasures of the two-wheeled steed. "Why did we ever stop?" he mused, "Bikes are the only way to traverse these distances." And he was right. The bicycle, a simple and efficient conveyance, carries one from one end of the campus to the other, as swiftly as the wind through the trees. A bowl of porridge and a few minutes of exertion can span a considerable distance. Yet, the path to the Thomas Building, a mere twenty-five-minute walk, becomes a mere five-minute jaunt on a bicycle, a saving of time that is both precious and necessary.

Yet, the road is not always kind. Pollock Road, the most direct path, is a treacherous one, a gauntlet of broken glass and potholes. And in the cold and the rain, the journey becomes a true test of endurance. But the alternatives, the alternatives of walking, are even more daunting. The thought of spending an extra half hour to an hour each day on foot, a total of more than two and a half hours each week, is a heavy burden to bear. The bicycle, despite its flaws, remains the swiftest and most reliable mode of transport.

The campus, in its ceaseless growth, must adapt to the needs of its inhabitants. The bicycle, a symbol of both simplicity and progress, must be embraced, not just for the sake of efficiency, but for the sake of the students themselves. For in this age of constant motion, to be still is to fall behind.

original_texts:
In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language.
